body:
Hello!

I have some rather... elaborate [macros](https://github.com/tildeio/helix/blob/master/src/macros/parser.rs) that is matching against a pretty [complex syntax](https://usehelix.com/documentation).

I think it's pretty impressive that this could be done without using procedural macros or compiler-plugins, but one down side is that when there is a syntax error (i.e. a macro mismatch) the error message could be pretty cryptic/useless.

In most of the cases, I could have easily added a "catch-all" rule for the invalid state and provide a better error message. However, I don't think there is a way to deliberately cause the compiler to bail-out from within a macro.

Would it be possible to have a compile-time equivalent of `panic!` for this scenario?

Example (using a run-time panic to illustrate the use case):

```rust
#![allow(unreachable_code)]

macro_rules! cons {
    ($car:tt, $cdr:tt) => { ($car, $cdr) };
    ($($args:tt),*) => { panic!("Expected 2 arguments, got {}: cons!({})", count!($($args)*), stringify!($($args),*)) };
}

macro_rules! count {
    () => { 0 };
    ($first:tt $($rest:tt)*) => { 1 + count!($($rest)*) };
}

fn main() {
    // works
    println!("{:?}", cons!(1, 2));
    
    // error
    println!("{:?}", cons!());
    println!("{:?}", cons!(1, 2, 3, 4));
}
```
